ce:section.ce:para:
This article reviewed the application of fluorescence assays based on various nanomaterials (e.g. gold nanomaterials, quantum dots, magnetic nanomaterials, carbon nanomaterials, MOFs) for the analyses of MCs in various seafood and aquaculture-related matrices (Fig. 2
                      & Table 1
                     ). Firstly, it mainly reviewed the mechanisms of nanomaterial-based fluorescence assays in MCs, including photoinduced electron transfer (PET), fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET), and inner-filter effect (IFE). PET is based on the interaction between fluorescent probes and MCs, and the rapid detection of MCs is achieved by photoexcitation-induced electron transfer; FRET is a method based on the phenomenon of non-radiative energy transfer between fluorescent probes, and the rapid detection of MCs is achieved by monitoring the energy transfer between fluorescent probes; and IFE takes advantage of the special properties of the nanomaterials in the inside its pore structure to achieve selective capture and detection of target molecules. Secondly, it also summarized the application of different fluorescence nanomaterials in MCs fluorescence assays, as well as their respective advantages and characteristics. In view of the urgent needs in the field of MCs assay, rapid assay of MCs by fluorescence technology is very promising. At present, although many studies have focused on the determination of MCs in lake water samples, there are relatively few reports on the application of nanomaterial-based fluorescence technology in the detection of MCs. The lack of research reports on nanomaterial-based fluorescence techniques in MCs detection may lead to problems such as inefficient monitoring, incomplete risk assessment, increased safety hazards for aquatic products, and limited technological development, which may affect the timely monitoring and control of MCs contamination. Therefore, it is necessary to thoroughly study and explore the potential applications of nanomaterial fluorescence technology in MCs detection to improve monitoring efficiency, protect public health and aquatic product quality. The study in this paper aims to explore the research progress of nanomaterial fluorescence for MCs detection in more depth and to provide guidance for the development of new efficient and sensitive methods for MCs detection. Through this review, we aim to highlight the importance of nanomaterial fluorescence technology for the detection of MCs in the seafood and aquaculture-related matrices and provide methodological guidelines for early screening, risk assessment and contamination monitoring of MCs. The significance of this research is to provide new technological approaches to address the challenges in seafood safety and aquaculture quality regulation, which is expected to contribute positively to the protection of public health and aquatic product quality.
